<HEADLINE>
<P>
* WINNIE PARRY CROOKSTON; CENTENARIAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Winnie Parry Crookston of Camarillo has died at the age of 103. 
</P>
<P>
 Her daughter, Maxine Schmidt of Camarillo, said her mother attributed her 
longevity to no drugs, alcohol or coffee. 
</P>
<P>
 "She lived a good clean life," Schmidt said. 
</P>
<P>
 Until last year, Crookston used a walker to take daily walks around her 
neighborhood at Ripley Street in the west end of Camarillo.  
</P>
<P>
 But eventually she had to give up her walks. 
</P>
<P>
 "She gradually wore out," Schmidt said. "She died of old age." 
</P>
<P>
 Crookston, who was born in Salt Lake City, Utah, moved to Ventura County in 
1971. She lived in Ventura for three years, then moved to Camarillo to be near 
her daughter.  
</P>
<P>
 Crookston was a member of the Mormon Church. Her husband, a salesman, died in 
1952. 
</P>
<P>
 In addition to her daughter, she is survived by a son, Wayne G. Crookston of 
Boise, Idaho, three grandchildren and four great-grandchildren.  
</P>
<P>
 Burial was last week in Salt Lake City. 
</P>
</TEXT>
