<HEADLINE>
<P>
PERSONAL VIEW: EXECUTIVE TRAVEL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * Name: George Elmstrom 
</P>
<P>
 * Position: President  
</P>
<P>
 * Company: Doctors Professional Consulting, Carmel 
</P>
<P>
 For over forty years, I have been traveling all over the globe, both lecturing 
and advising professionals.  
</P>
<P>
 In the early days, there was little attention paid to burnout, fatigue and 
stresses of frequent changes of planes and lodgings.But with time, it became 
obvious that there must be a better way to conserve energy, be more productive 
and arrive fresh. 
</P>
<P>
 Premium hotels are a better way and are worth the money. Where possible I 
sought out a Ritz-Carlton. The usual 24-hour room service was a true blessing 
since there was no need to search for, skip or rush a meal. The security system 
alone, as with all fine hotels, warrants the extra cost. And what great 
restaurants for discussions! 
</P>
<P>
 If there are company budget limitations against the top hotels, I either pay 
the extra cost myself or I constrict four days of work and meetings into two 
days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
