<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Jerry Hicks and Mark Platte 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 LOTS OF COMPANY: Left-hander Chuck Finley may be the highest-paid member of 
the California Angels, but he's far from being the highest-paid player in major 
league baseball. His $3,875,000 for this year is 44th on the current money 
list, figures released Tuesday show. Finley is 10th among all pitchers. . . . 
The Angels do stand out in one category: Only three teams -- the Montreal 
Expos, San Diego Padres and Florida Marlins -- have fewer millionaire players 
than the Angels, who have six. 
</P>
<P>
 CHEAP THRILLS? How do the owners pay all those high salaries? By making the 
fans pay. But a night at Anaheim Stadium is still a better bargain than most 
places. . . . Team Marketing Report, which annually assesses the cost of 
baseball attendance, ranks the Angels 22nd out of 28 in average expense. It 
says a family of four will spend an average $90.24 there -- a 6.7% increase 
this year. It's $115.25 at Yankee Stadium. The best bargain: Cincinnati -- the 
only one under $80. 
</P>
<P>
 SAIL TALK: Hank Dekker of San Francisco was driving race cars when he began 
losing his eyesight. By 1978, he was blind. That didn't stop his love of 
outdoor sports. He took up sailing with sighted friends, then alone, and 
started his own charter service. Next fall he plans to become the first blind 
man to sail the Atlantic alone. . . . Dekker talks about his sailing today at 1 
p.m. -- and again Thursday and Friday -- at the Newport Boat Show at the 
Newport Dunes resort. 
</P>
<P>
 SAVE A TREE: Financial woes for socialites Danny and Susie Hernandez continue. 
With Danny in federal prison and both he and Susie awaiting sentencing for 
fraud April 22, the bank has foreclosed on their $800,000 Mission Viejo home 
and this week evicted Susie and her children. Struggling for cash, Susie began 
selling the palm trees and bushes on the property to local landscapers just 
before eviction. . . . "She's doing what she can to keep food on the table," 
says Newport Beach attorney Scott Wellman, a family friend. "They bring in a 
few hundred dollars each." 
</P>
