<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFCASE: HEALTH CARE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
Compiled by James M. Gomez / Times staff writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Fast-Paced Medicine: Integrated Health Services Inc. is expanding its business 
to accommodate patients on the run. 
</P>
<P>
 The Orange company said that it is adding an outpatient center at its Orange 
Hills facility. Outpatient care is one of the fastest-growing segments of the 
health care industry because it allows patients to see doctors and be treated 
in settings that are less expensive than hospitals. 
</P>
<P>
 Company spokesman Phillip Joujon-Roche said that the addition of the 
outpatient center is a natural for Integrated Health Services, which operates 
so-called subacute centers. 
</P>
<P>
 Subacute centers are a hybrid of hospital wards and nursing homes. They 
accommodate patients too sick to send home but not ill enough to require the 
24-hour care that a hospital provides. 
</P>
</TEXT>
