<HEADLINE>
<P>
TV RATINGS; CBS CHALKS UP A WINNER IN 'CHRISTY' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DANIEL CERONE 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 CBS may have another "Dr. Quinn, Medicine Woman" on its hands after the 
two-hour premiere Sunday night of the new family series "Christy," which 
finished No. 5 for the week in household ratings and generated hundreds of 
phone calls to CBS on Monday from grateful viewers. 
</P>
<P>
 But overall, CBS narrowly lost the weekly prime-time ratings race again to 
ABC, which has banged out four straight wins after CBS dominated the Nielsens 
during the Winter Olympics, according to A. C. Nielsen Co. figures released 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
 After "Dr. Quinn" found a solid audience on Saturday night, CBS developed 
"Christy"--starring Kellie Martin, Tyne Daly and Tess Harper--based on the 
award-winning novel about a young woman who leaves a privileged city life to 
teach at a missionary school in the Smokey Mountains before World War I. 
</P>
<P>
 ABC scored big Wednesday by sandwiching two new sitcoms--"Thunder Alley" and 
"These Friends of Mine," starring comedian Ellen DeGeneres--with dual episodes 
of the season's No. 1 program, "Home Improvement." All four shows Wednesday 
finished in the Top 10, along with the one-two punch Tuesday of "Roseanne" and 
the debut of "These Friends of Mine." 
</P>
<P>
 ABC's Friday debut of "Sister, Sister," a sitcom about two identical twins, 
finished a respectable No. 18 for the week, ABC's best performance in that 8:30 
p.m. time slot since 1987. Southland Ratings 
</P>
