<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: ANAHEIM; FREEWAY CREW ERROR CAUSES LENGTHY SNARL TRAFFIC 
DELAY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 An error in judgment by a crew working on improvements to the Riverside 
Freeway caused an hourlong traffic delay Tuesday morning, with westbound 
traffic backed up for about seven miles, according to Caltrans and the 
California Highway Patrol. 
</P>
<P>
 The mix-up occurred when a stripping crew for Traffic Safety, one of the 
subcontracting companies working on the Riverside Freeway project, ground up 
more asphalt than they could clean up within the time allotted and had to 
remain on the job nearly five hours past its 5 a.m. daily shutdown time, said 
Caltrans spokesman Albert Miranda. 
</P>
<P>
 The grinding is needed to erase old stripping, which is being replaced with 
new stripes that conform to new alignments on the widened road, Miranda said. 
</P>
<P>
 The work was being done on a section of the freeway between Kraemer Boulevard 
and the Orange Freeway. 
</P>
<P>
 Miranda said car-pool lanes are being added to the Riverside Freeway and 
improvements are being made to the on- and off-ramps at Tustin Avenue and at 
the Kraemer Boulevard and North Glassell Street exchange, all part of the 
two-year project. 
</P>
<P>
 "The project has been going on for almost a year and we've only had a few of 
these (mistakes)," Miranda said. "We try to keep them to a minimum by making 
sure that contractor and subcontractor coordinate their activities around 
normal commuter hours. 
</P>
<P>
 "This is a onetime incident that is not going to happen again," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
