<HEADLINE>
<P>
STREET BEAT: THE FIGHT AGAINST CRIME: NOTES FROM THE FRONT; LEARNING THE ABCS 
OF POLICE LINGO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ANN W. O'NEILL, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Used to be, everybody who was anybody at the Los Angeles Police Department had 
an acronym. The LAPD elevated the acronym to an art form with a veritable 
epidemic of acronym-itis during the 1970s. 
</P>
<P>
 The LAPD became riddled with units and divisions with $75 names. For example, 
paroled criminals were tracked by STAR TREC, which stood for the System to 
Account for Releases ThatRequire Extra Caution. 
</P>
<P>
 While the urge to create short, snappy names for the things police officers do 
has eased with time, the acronym continues to leave its indelible mark on LAPD 
culture. 
</P>
<P>
 Even now, at the Devonshire station, cans of dog food decorate the desks of 
the fingerprint team, or Area Latent Print Officers, commonly known as ALPO. 
</P>
<P>
 "If you have an acronym, you have to have a coffee mug and a T-shirt," said 
Deputy Chief Mark A. Kroeker, former commander of the LAPD's Valley Division. 
"If you really emerge, you get a baseball cap with the acronym on it." 
</P>
<P>
 Acronyms provided the perfect marriage between police work's military and 
bureaucratic influences, as officers bandied about words such as interface and 
system to make them work. 
</P>
<P>
 Occasionally, such rampant creativity led to controversy. 
</P>
<P>
 CRASH, for example, remains a popular acronym for a gang unit once known as 
TRASH. 
</P>
<P>
 CRASH -- short for the quaintly named Community Resources Against Street 
Hoodlums -- was the LAPD's substitute when some community leaders objected to 
the politically incorrect TRASH: Total Resources Against Street Hoodlums. 
</P>
<P>
 STORM was born out of the Hollywood Division's desire to dispatch its cars 
more efficiently, and initially stood for System to Overcome Residual 
Mismanagement. But the name was changed to System to Optimize Radio Car 
Management after the earlier version ruffled feathers at central dispatch 
downtown. 
</P>
<P>
 Kroeker is an armchair student of the acronym, an admitted acro-phile. 
</P>
<P>
 Even before he made sergeant, Kroeker said, he aspired to create the longest, 
most bureaucratic-sounding acronym. He succeeded with CONSTRUCT, the Committee 
on a New Systematized Transfer of Records Under a Centralized Terminal. 
</P>
<P>
 It had to do with improving juvenile offender records, Kroeker explained. "I 
laughed with glee. It looked totally official," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 Later, in an oral exam for promotion, Kroeker was asked to give the meaning of 
his own acronym. He got that one right. 
</P>
<P>
 "The test of a true LAPD acronym is when they ask you about it at your oral 
interview," he said. Candidates for promotion can spend hours studying long 
lists of acronyms. Kroeker can rattle them off at an impressive clip. 
</P>
<P>
 Officers who have the political clout to pull duty in the office of Chief of 
Police Willie L. Williams enjoy the prestige of a short, sweet acronym that 
says it all: COP. 
</P>
<P>
 But those who deal with the press, work for CRO -- acronym-ese for the 
Community Relations Office. But they pronounce it "crow," and sometimes they 
wind up eating it. 
</P>
<P>
 PACE is not just a picante sauce. It is also the LAPD'S Police Assisted 
Community Enhancement unit, which helps citizens pick up trash and remove 
graffiti. 
</P>
<P>
 But the best-known acronyms are those that ooze coolness: CRASH and CAPS and 
BAD CATS. 
</P>
<P>
 CRASH, the gang unit that used to be TRASH, is found at most police stations. 
CAPS is the Crimes Against Persons Section, which handles everything from 
robbery to rape. BAD CATS is a double whammy, acronym-wise. BAD is the 
Burglary-Auto theft Division (although you could argue it should be BATD) and 
CATS is the Commercial Auto Theft Section. In case you missed that, they 
investigate car thefts. 
</P>
<P>
 "In the height of the acronym craze, "We used to have sheets of acronyms 
published," Kroeker said. "I've always been delighted with them and I have 
always poked fun at them." 
</P>
<P>
 Count us among the converted. 
</P>
<P>
 Henceforth, STREET stands for Space Totally Reserved to Entertain, Enlighten 
and Teach. We have yet to settle on what BEAT means, though Better Editing At 
The Times comes to mind. 
</P>
</TEXT>
